
Office/standard tower (Dell XPS example)
  * Front: CD/DVD optical drive, physical power button, SD card reader, combo 1/8‑inch audio jack (headset + mic), three blue SuperSpeed USB‑A, one USB‑C SuperSpeed.
  * Back upper left: three 1/8‑inch audio jacks forming a 5.1 surround sound output cluster.
  * Back video: one DisplayPort (rectangular with top‑left corner cut), one HDMI.
  * Back USB: four blue SuperSpeed USB 3.x (up to 5 Gb/s) and two black USB 2.0 (slower, not SuperSpeed).
  * Network: one RJ45 Ethernet jack (supports 10/100/1000 Mb/s depending on NIC).
  * Expansion area: 4 slots total; blanks used when no card installed.
  * Example GPUs: one card with 3 DisplayPorts + 1 HDMI; another with 1 DVI (older standard, largely replaced by HDMI/DisplayPort).
  * Power: small power supply taking ~half the case width; thumbscrews on side panel for access.

Gaming tower (Alienware example)
  * Front: vertical CD/DVD drive, 1/8‑inch headset jack, three SuperSpeed USB‑A, one SuperSpeed USB‑C.
  * Rear cable cover: removable shroud hiding port cluster and cables.
  * Power: full‑width power supply across entire bottom rear.
  * Expansion: powerful GPU occupying two slots, with one HDMI + three DisplayPorts; dual‑slot designs allow extra cooling/fans.
  * Rear audio: 7.1 audio cluster with multiple colored 1/8‑inch jacks plus an optical SPDIF port for high‑quality digital audio.  
  * Rear USB cluster:
    * Top row: two non‑SuperSpeed USB 2.0 (good for mouse, keyboard, mic).
    * Middle rows: USB 3.x SuperSpeed—left side USB‑C, right side USB‑A.
    * Bottom row: two more non‑SuperSpeed USB 2.0 (no “SS” marking).
    
  * Network: RJ45 Ethernet jack in the USB cluster.
  * Security: Kensington lock slot (looks similar to USB‑C but with lock icon) for physically securing the case with a cable.

All‑in‑one PC (Dell 27‑inch example)
  * Form factor: looks like a thin monitor with built‑in webcam but houses full PC components.
  * Rear ports (left to right): Kensington lock, DC barrel‑style power input, two HDMI ports, one SuperSpeed USB‑C, RJ45 Ethernet, one standard USB‑A, three SuperSpeed USB 3.x, 1/8‑inch audio jack, SD memory card slot.

Big-picture items to know
  * Be able to visually identify: USB‑A vs USB‑C, blue SuperSpeed vs black USB 2.0, DisplayPort, HDMI, DVI, RJ45, 1/8‑inch audio jacks, optical SPDIF, SD card slots, DC power jack, and Kensington lock.
  * Recognize which ports commonly appear on: office towers, gaming towers, and all‑in‑one systems, and how their power supplies and expansion slots differ.
  * Remember exam style: image of a back panel with a labeled connector (A, B, C) where you must name the connector and/or state its function (network, video, audio, etc.).

