Direct Answers (clear & concise):
  Office/Standard Tower (Dell XPS-style)
    Front: Optical drive, power button, SD card reader, combo 3.5 mm audio (headset + mic), 3× blue SuperSpeed USB-A, 1× USB-C SuperSpeed.
    Back upper left: 3× 3.5 mm audio jacks (5.1 surround).
    Back video: 1× DisplayPort (rectangular, top-left corner cut), 1× HDMI.
    Back USB: 4× blue SuperSpeed USB 3.x (up to 5 Gbps), 2× black USB 2.0 (slower, no “SS”).
    Network: 1× RJ45 Ethernet (10/100/1000 Mbps depending on NIC).
    Expansion: 4 slots (blanks when empty).
    GPU examples: Cards with 3× DisplayPort + 1× HDMI or older DVI.
    Power: Small PSU (~half case width), side panel with thumbscrews.

  Gaming Tower (Alienware-style)
    Front: Vertical optical drive, 3.5 mm headset jack, 3× SuperSpeed USB-A, 1× USB-C.
    Rear: Removable cable shroud.
    Power: Full-width PSU at bottom rear.
    Expansion: Thick GPU taking 2 slots (better cooling), e.g., 1× HDMI + 3× DisplayPort.
    Rear audio: 7.1 cluster (multiple colored 3.5 mm jacks) + optical SPDIF (digital audio).
    Rear USB: Top & bottom rows = black USB 2.0 (mouse/keyboard/mic); middle rows = SuperSpeed   USB 3.x (USB-C + USB-A).
    Network: RJ45 in the USB cluster.
    Security: Kensington lock slot (looks like a small lock icon, not USB-C).

  All-in-One PC (Dell 27" example)
    Thin monitor-like body with built-in webcam and full PC inside.
    Rear ports (left to right): Kensington lock, DC barrel power, 2× HDMI, 1× SuperSpeed USB-C, RJ45, 1× standard USB-A, 3× SuperSpeed USB 3.x, 3.5 mm audio, SD card slot.

Big-Picture Items (Exam-Ready):
    Visually identify: USB-A vs USB-C, blue “SS” USB 3.x vs black USB 2.0, DisplayPort (cut corner), HDMI, DVI (older), RJ45 (Ethernet), 3.5 mm audio jacks (various colors), optical SPDIF, SD slot, DC power jack, Kensington lock.
    Know differences: Office towers = compact PSU + modest expansion; Gaming towers = big PSU + thick GPU + better audio; All-in-ones = integrated + limited internal expansion but many rear ports.
    Exam style: Expect images of back panels – you pick the connector (A/B/C) and state its function (video, network, audio, power, security, etc.).

Quick Semantic Tree (roots → trunk → leaves):
  Root: Computers need to connect input/output/peripherals/power.
  Trunk: Ports = standardized physical interfaces for data, video, audio, network, power.
  Branches: USB (data/power), Video (DisplayPort/HDMI/DVI), Audio (3.5 mm + SPDIF), Network (RJ45), Security (Kensington).
  Leaves: Form factor changes layout (office = simple, gaming = high-performance, AIO = integrated). Blue = SuperSpeed (faster), black = USB 2.0 (legacy/slow devices). This directly feeds into troubleshooting (Domain 5) and mobile/device support (Domain 1).
